:::summary
Charlemagne (c. 747–814), King of the Franks and first Holy Roman Emperor, united most of Western Europe under his rule for the first time since the fall of Rome. A devout Christian and tireless patron of education and the arts, his reign launched the Carolingian Renaissance and laid the political and cultural foundations upon which medieval European civilization was built.
:::

